item.title: Harris to livestream with Oprah, Trump to address Israeli-American group
item.description: Vice President Kamala Harris and former President Donald Trump are stepping up their campaign efforts. Harris will join Oprah Winfrey in Michigan, while Trump speaks at the Israeli-American Council event. The “Uncommitted” Democratic protest movement won't endorse Harris but urges votes against Trump. These activities follow a significant Federal Reserve interest rate cut.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Mark Robinson stays in NC governor's race amid bombshell report backlash
item.description: North Carolina Lieutenant Governor Mark Robinson, the Republican nominee for governor, is under fire following a CNN report alleging he made inflammatory comments on a porn site’s message board over a decade ago. Despite some GOP members urging him to step aside, Robinson denies the allegations and vows to continue his campaign.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Taylor Swift: A pop phenomenon with presidential-level appeal on voters
item.description: Taylor Swift endorsed Vice President Kamala Harris for the 2024 presidential race on Instagram, sparking political discussions. A poll indicates a partisan divide in opinions about Swift, with higher favorability among Democrats than Republicans. Former President Donald Trump criticized Swift on Truth Social, underscoring the polarized reactions to her endorsement.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Pakistan blames Afghanistan for supporting terrorism
item.description: Pakistan has raised alarms at the UN Security Council regarding a severe terrorism threat from Afghanistan, emphasizing the rise of militant groups like Tehreek-i-Taliban Pakistan (TTP). Ambassador Munir Akram accused the Afghan interim government of backing TTP and called for global cooperation to tackle this issue. Pakistan plans further national actions against these threats.
item.dc:creator: Omer Farooq Khan

item.title: Manhunt ends: YouTube couple finds Kentucky highway shooter's body in wilderness
item.description: A manhunt for Joseph Couch, who allegedly shot at cars on Kentucky’s Interstate 75, ended when a couple found a decomposing body believed to be his. Couch had injured five people and evaded authorities for nearly two weeks in the Daniel Boone National Forest. An autopsy will confirm the identity.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: US elections: Muslim Americans turn to Jill Steins in big blow to Kamala Harris
item.description: Jill Stein of the Green Party is drawing considerable support from Arab-American and Muslim voters in the 2024 presidential race. Frustration with the Biden administration's backing of Israel has led many to favor Stein over Kamala Harris. This voter shift could influence outcomes in key battleground states such as Michigan, Arizona, and Wisconsin.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: $1 million yacht full of fireworks sinks after explosive blaze in California Marina
item.description: A luxury yacht called 'The Admiral,' valued at nearly $1 million, caught fire and sank in Marina del Rey, California. Loaded with fireworks and ammunition, it ignited a massive blaze. Despite efforts from the Los Angeles Fire Department, the vessel sank within two hours. The cause of the fire is still being investigated.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Melania Trump reportedly frustrated by Kari Lake's closeness with Donald Trump
item.description: Speculations about tension between Donald and Melania Trump have arisen due to Kari Lake's frequent visits to Mar-a-Lago. The former Arizona gubernatorial candidate has been praised by Trump, leading to rumors of Melania's discomfort. Despite these claims, Lake’s senior adviser called the allegations 'ridiculous,' stating she stays elsewhere with her husband.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Ohio officials approve language saying anti-gerrymandering measure calls for the opposite
item.description: Ohio election officials have approved controversial ballot language for Issue 1, intended to prevent gerrymandering but described as requiring it. The proposal aims to replace the current map-making system with a citizen-led commission. This approval follows a state Supreme Court order correcting misleading sections in the description.

item.title: Israel's pager, walkie-talkie attacks a 'declaration of war', says Hezbollah chief Nasrallah
item.description: Hezbollah leader Hassan Nasrallah condemned an attack on the group's communication devices that killed over 30 people and injured thousands. He described it as a severe blow and potential declaration of war. The incident, likely carried out by Israel, has heightened tensions, leading to ongoing exchanges between Hezbollah and Israeli forces with significant casualties.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Trump and Harris neck and neck in Pennsylvania: Latest Poll
item.description: Former President Donald Trump and Vice President Kamala Harris are neck-and-neck in the presidential race, each securing 47 per cent support nationally. In Pennsylvania, a crucial battleground state, Harris leads by 4 points. Demographic trends show Trump’s advantage among men and seniors, while Harris gains strong backing from women and younger voters.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Xi Jinping’s nationalism faces reckoning after murder of Japanese boy
item.description: The killing of a Japanese boy in Shenzhen underscores the dangers of growing Chinese nationalism. Authorities call it an isolated case, but online reactions point to deeper social and economic issues. Such incidents could hinder China's efforts to attract foreign investment during economic struggles. Beijing has reined in its “Wolf Warrior” diplomats, and is trying to stabilize ties with the US.

item.title: Hole in fuel hose caused fire in Cathay Pacific A350 flight, Hong Kong probe finds
item.description: A Cathay Pacific Airbus A350 encountered a fire caused by a ruptured fuel hose, leading to an emergency return to Hong Kong. The incident raised concerns about engine reliability and prompted inspections of 15 other aircraft in the fleet. Recommendations were issued for Rolls-Royce to provide inspection requirements for the affected components.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Hong Kong man jailed for T-shirt protest slogan
item.description: A Hong Kong man has been sentenced to 14 months in prison for sedition under the city's new national security law after wearing a T-shirt with a protest slogan. The court ruled that the slogan could incite secession, making this the first sedition conviction under the new legislation.

item.title: Israeli citizen arrested for alleged Iranian-assisted plot to assassinate Netanyahu
item.description: Israeli police and Shin Bet have apprehended an Israeli citizen accused of being recruited by Iranian intelligence to orchestrate the assassinations of key officials, including Prime Minister Netanyahu. The suspect, a businessman with ties to Turkey and Iran, was reportedly involved in several security missions within Israel and received payment for his actions.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Walkie-talkies in Lebanon blasts were made at least a decade ago
item.description: Among the many outstanding questions is how explosive materials were planted in the devices. If the Icom walkie-talkies were first manufactured a decade ago, it’s possible they were modified well after sale to their original customers.

item.title: Inside the Brooklyn federal jail where Sean 'Diddy' Combs is locked up: violence, squalor and death
item.description: Sean "Diddy" Combs has been incarcerated at Brooklyn's Metropolitan Detention Center following his arrest on sex trafficking charges. The facility, notorious for its poor conditions and safety concerns, houses approximately 1,200 detainees. Combs' legal team contends that the jail is inappropriate for pretrial detention given its history of violence and recent fatalities.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Donald Trump buys fans burgers and pays with Bitcoin at New York bar
item.description: Donald Trump visited a Bitcoin-themed bar in New York, purchasing burgers with Bitcoin to garner support from cryptocurrency enthusiasts. He is promoting a new project called World Liberty Financial. Despite facing protests outside, Trump's appearance received applause from both Bitcoin supporters and his loyalists inside the bar.

item.title: North Korea tests ballistic missile capable of carrying 'super-large' warhead
item.description: North Korea reported testing a tactical ballistic missile carrying a super-large warhead and an upgraded strategic cruise missile, overseen by Kim Jong Un. He emphasized enhancing military capabilities for self-defense. This development aligns with strengthened ties between North Korea and Russia, and precedes parliamentary measures expected to escalate tensions with South Korea.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Had to sign or face consequences': Venezuela’s opposition leader claims he was forced to admit defeat
item.description: Venezuelan opposition candidate Edmundo Gonzalez Urrutia disclosed he was coerced into signing a letter conceding defeat to Nicolas Maduro. Now granted asylum in Madrid, Urrutia insists the letter is invalid and maintains his electoral victory. Numerous countries refuse to acknowledge Maduro's win without a full vote breakdown from the CNE.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk
